Marvin, you have hit upon another example of "unfinished business"
within X.500.  As you point out, fast, low-overhead searches and
large, distributed, relational databases don't mix.  Thus, the
attributes used in X.500 names fall into (or are put into) a
hierarchical relationship.  Distributing the database along the lines
of this hierarchy makes it easier and to find faster to do searches
with a complete name as a key, since the name can be directly mapped
into the location of its associated entry.

As it turns out, the hierarchy does not have to be used as a pattern
for distributing the database.  (Internet nameservers work in an
analagous way.)  The directory service agents can store information
for multiple subtrees with different parent nodes.  Mechanisms are
provided to help the DSAs to cope with this.  In these cases, the DSAs
can store and make available whatever "knowledge" they've gained about
the actual distribution of the database.  Alas, that information is in
human-readable form only, suitable for administrators but not for
processing by other DSAs.

--Debbie

